## The night the river hands the day back to you.

Luxor asks a lot of you by daylight. It's magnificent and it's relentless — the heat, the scale, the sheer accumulated weight of three thousand years, all demanding to be understood before lunch. And then the sun goes down, and the river offers you the antidote: a table on the water, dinner brought to you, and the whole city softening into lights and reflections as you drift.

There is a version of this sold cheap and loud — a floating banquet hall for three hundred, a buffet and a belly-dancer and a bus back at ten. This is the quiet opposite of that.

## Your table, your pace, your river

Private here means the evening is yours. Your own table on the deck, dinner served rather than queued for, and no timetable but the slow one the current sets. You talk, you eat, you watch — the East Bank temples floodlit and doubled in the black water, the Corniche lit up, the odd felucca crossing your bow with its sail catching the last of the light.

We put you on the water at the right hour on purpose: golden hour first, when the river turns molten and the sails around you glow, and then the long, easy fade into a lit-up evening. By the second course the day has stopped pulling at you. By the far bank you've forgotten you were ever tired.

> The temples make you feel the weight of history. The river, at night, quietly hands the evening back to you.

## Handled, so dinner is just dinner

Pickup from your hotel, the boat readied, the table set, the food arranged around whatever you like, and your consigliere on the phone if anything's needed. You arrive, you sit, you're looked after — the rarest thing on a busy trip.

Bring it to the end of a full day, or an evening that matters. In a country of grand, demanding wonders, a private table on the Nile at night is the one that simply lets you exhale.
